 been in the classical case of abelian varieties. While the book does examine this area, it focuses on the nonclassical case. The general theory turns out to be very rich, such as in the unexpected connections of finite dimensional and infinite dimensional representation theory of real, semisimple Lie groups. The authors give the complete classification of Hodge representations, a topic that should become a standard in the finite-dimensional representation theory of noncompact, real, semisimple Lie groups. They also indicate that in the future, a connection seems ready to be made between Lie groups that admit discrete series representations and the study of automorphic cohomology on "ients of Mumford-Tate domains by arithmetic groups. Bringing together complex geometry, representation theory, and arithmetic, this book opens up a fresh perspective on an important subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aMumford-Tate groups. 7aMATHEMATICS / Complex Analysis.2bisacsh  aDeligne torus integer.  aGalois group.  aGrothendieck conjecture.  aHodge decomposition.  aHodge domain.  aHodge filtration.  aHodge orientation.  aHodge representation.  aHodge structure.  aHodge tensor.  aHodge theory.  aKubota rank.  aLie algebra representation.  aLie group.  aMumford-Tate domain.  aMumford-Tate group.  aMumford-Tate subdomain.  aNoether-Lefschetz locus.  aVogan diagram method.  aWeyl group.  aabelian variety.  aabsolute Hodge class.  aalgebraic geometry.  aarithmetic group.  aautomorphic cohomology.  aclassical group.  acompact dual.  acomplex manifold.  acomplex multiplication Hodge structure.  acomplex multiplication.  aendomorphism algebra.  aexceptional group.  aholomorphic mapping.  ahomogeneous complex manifold.  ahomomorphism.  amixed Hodge structure.  am